segments.text: Since I was a student?
Well, I guess the major change that I immediately sensed when I came back was the transition from an all-military school
from a compulsory military to a non-compulsory military.

When I was here in the 50s it was compulsory and everybody was in the Corps with the exception of some returning veterans who was coming back from World War II and still in the educational environment.
But it was an all-military school, an all-male school.
The emphasis, as I understood it then, and also as I seem to sense it when I came back in 69, was it was an undergraduate teaching institution.
They may have had graduate programs at that time.
I certainly don't recall in the 50s.
And I do not recall any kind of major emphasis in the research area when I was a student.
It seemed like the faculty were here to teach and did little else.
The other thing is I recall at that time there was, it seemed to me anyway, a large percentage of the faculty were A&M graduates.
That's not particularly bad.
I make no value judgment on that one way or the other, but that seemed to be the situation.
But I came back in 69.
It was evident, and other than the physical facilities, a great change in the physical facilities of the university.
There's no comparing that.
The change the university went through when Dr. Williams was president in terms of remodeling the campus and trying to keep the campus up in terms of building, it was just a phenomenal change.
There's no way to describe that.
So there was a... Dr. Williams was the...
was the president of the university after President Rudder, Jack Williams.
He was an excellent president.

I think one of the major contributions he made to this university was putting its campus in order, physically in order, in addition to the growth of the academic programs to make it truly a university.
It was a college in 1950.
was primarily agriculture and engineering.
I'm sure that there were some other programs, but I was not aware of them.
They just didn't have the emphasis.
It was engineering and agriculture.
Well, when I came in 69, I sensed a transition occurring then, that the idea was to have a faculty member that could be a researcher and a teacher.
And it seemed like from that point on, in the early 70s and so forth,
The idea was to try to employ people that could do research as well as teach.
And as I began to move into administrative positions where I was more aware of what I considered to be the administration's policy, that was true.
There was an emphasis being placed on research and teaching.
And in the 50s, where you had a teaching faculty,
that could probably do research, I guess.
I don't know.
Now we have a greater percentage of our faculty that are research faculty that can also teach.
And in my opinion, I don't think we have degraded the teaching quality of our faculty.
We've added a faculty that has an additional characteristic.
Do you think that the emphasis on research may have gone too far at the expense of teaching quality?
I think that the seeds have been planted that can take us too far.
There's been a lot of criticism of these National Science Foundation research grants for some of the topics that have been
seemingly impractical topics that have been researched, and this has led to a lot of opposition to this program in Congress.

In fact, I believe the budget for the whole program was left out of, the money for the whole program was inadvertently left out of the budget and had to go back and be put in, but the funds haven't been cut on this.
Because a lot of congressmen have been saying that some of these research projects don't have any real practical value.
What's your idea on this?
Well, that, historically... Is research, for the sake of research, desirable?
Historically, the National Science Foundation has not funded engineering projects.
This, of course, has been always a thorn in the side of the engineering community that we do not have a federal agency that looks into or supplies or funds engineering research per se.
I don't know, 10 years ago or so, a small arm of the National Science Foundation was added to try to take care of engineering-related research.
I think that in the types of projects you're mentioning, you won't find one of those being called out that was actually being funded by the Engineering Army.
The Engineering Army has their emphasis more on funding
programs to solve problems.
Our emphasis here in the college, and I would suppose the university, is more applied as opposed to developing knowledge for knowledge sake.
I know at least in the College of Engineering our programs are directed, research is directed at solving a particular problem or a set of problems.
What are some of the
challenges that an industrial engineer would expect in the 1980s.
I was going to say before I say that another part of the growth has been in the research area and it's been undergirded and has been strengthened through the engineering experiment station.
I don't know exactly when the engineering experiment station
begin to move into an expanding role of research.
It seemed like to me it must have occurred sometime in the 60s.
But with the expanding role of the Engineering Experiment Station, the concept of research, as well as teaching at the college and university level, that became more into focus.
Prior to the real growth and emphasis in research by the Engineering Experiment Station, we were a teaching institution.

As the Experiment Station grew and matured and took its rightful role in serving the Texas community, which has to do with research, serving the Texas community in proper sense, then the idea of research in the College of Texas A&M began to establish its own position and take a rightful position in teaching.
That occurred, it seems like to me, in the last 10 years.
When I came in 69, I was aware of the Engineering Experiment Station, but its role was not as focused as it became in the next 10 years.
to really try to meet the needs, technological needs of the industry and the people of the state of Texas.
And when they saw that, when the administration and the leadership saw that, then research became a greater focus.
And it took sort of a rightful position with teaching.
Now, what was that question?
What future challenges will industrial engineers expect to see in the 80s?
Well, everything is going to cost more.
And the industrial engineer will be asked to perform decision-making roles that will permit growth and production to occur in a more economical fashion so as to guarantee profits.
In other words, updating plant equipment to make them more efficient.
Right, and that's it.

Now, the difficulty of that is that the technology is more complex, and the idea of saying I'm going to make a decision between the two types of lathes 25 years ago is not like saying make a decision between two different types of robots or numerical control machinery.
Because you talk about millions of dollars of investment per atom.
So what the industrial engineer is going to have to do, he's going to have to improve his tools of what we call simulation.
What we teach our students now is the ability to simulate complex processes.
By that I mean to quantify, to quantitatively describe them.
put that on a computer.
If you can quantitatively describe your system and you know the variables that are going to relate to the operation of that system, then you can program it and change them by computer.
And within seconds, you can see what, if you make this change, what the impact will be, or you make this change, what the impact will be.

The challenge will be for our industrial engineers to be able to quantifiably simulate complex manufacturing systems so that they can help management make the correct decisions in planning for productivity and technology growth.
If we're ever going to get back ahead in the productivity game, my feeling is the industrial engineers are going to get us there.
That's the general feeling of the engineering community now.
It's probably that particular item that industrial engineering will actually hang its hat on for the next decade, 25 years.
Actually be that item that industrial engineering will effectively move into what we call the engineering community.
You may not be aware of it, but industrial engineering is a fairly young engineering technology.
Organized itself, as far as the society is concerned, is about as early as 1946.
Industrial engineering, as such, is an all-new period of non-acceptance by the other engineers, whereas chemical engineers are mechanical engineers.
Electrical engineers have been around years and years and years.
Do we really need something called industrial engineering?
industrial engineering has for the past 25 years or so been groping through the maze of technology trying to find that item.
They hang their hats over and say, this is what industrial engineers do.
I think the productivity issue is what you mean by that.
Regarding this productivity issue, the way I understand it, it's said that the plants in the United States are not as cost-efficient as those in West Germany or Japan.
Is that true?
Yes.
Of course, you say, why aren't they?
There's a number of reasons why they're not.
But the main reason is that they're outdated and outmoded.
Since the Japanese...
West German plants were built right after World War II.
These others were built earlier.
That's exactly right.
The idea that our plants are outmoded and the idea that our plants are operating at the less than maximum efficiency.
And that's the reason we're here.
Most of the companies, to get these plants updated, this won't be a problem.
Most of the companies are looking at, that we're aware of, are looking at a 10-year program of what they call re-industrialization.
I think that the U.S. is going to go through a new industrial revolution that they experienced and the whole world experienced it so many years ago.
And during this time, I think we'll be upgrading and modifying and modernizing our manufacturing systems.
It's going to be very critical that during this process that the right decision is made.
You don't want to buy machinery and put in, modernize your plant and make the wrong decision on what you buy.
I think that's part of the inflation problem is the fact that our plants are not always up to date as they should be.
It's a production problem.
Things cost more because we don't produce as much.
I sincerely believe that.
I agree with Bill Grimm.
Let me ask you one other thing I should have asked you earlier.
When you came in 69, about how many students were there in industrial engineering?
There were about 1,800 a day.
How has this changed in these 12 years?
I've been able to tell you how it's changed since I became a partner here.
We had a little over 900 students when I became a partner here.
So it's doubled in six years.
If I were to extrapolate back to 69 and recalling some of the things Brother told me, we must have been somewhere around
So you've tripled in 12 years.
Is there anything else that you'd like to say before we close?
Anything that I didn't touch on that I should have?
Well...

You know, I was going to say, I'm going to sort of pass on this changes, in addition to physical changes, which is evident, and enrollment changes, which is less evident and yet evident to the person that's probably in there, is this research teaching emphasis.
Another major change that's occurred seems to be that
Texas A&M has been a growth in graduate education.
Of course, this may be tied to the growth of research and kind of change, given the emphasis of research.
But there's been a major change in terms of graduate education.
A&M has always been a very strong undergraduate institution.
And as such, it's made quite an impact
but we have never made a major impact at other institutions of higher learning.
We just don't have that many faculty, people who are on PhDs teaching elsewhere.
One reason we would never have the graduate program.
I think that we're gonna see in the next,

25 years certainly increase in the number of Texas A&M University PhDs teaching in other universities as such can't do anything but help us increase our image in the academic community the academic community
unfortunately does not rate another university in terms of its undergraduate program per se.
Those students go in the industry and make your reputation in the industry.
Other academic institutions generally measure you in terms of your students that you put out and become faculty researchers and publish at other institutions.
We're behind the power curve on that because we have not had the graduate programs.
We're going to see that catching up shortly.
Even though still a lot of our students, even our graduate students are going into the industry, there is an increasing percentage going into teaching now.
And we're going to see the image of Texas A&M certainly increase in the academic community as a result.
Is there anything else?
No, I don't think so.
I appreciate you taking the time to talk with us when it comes to health.
Are you sure?
It seems like I'm wandering around here.
Thank you.
